00:00:11.016 --> 00:00:14.516
Koshari found its way to Egypt in the 19th
century

00:00:14.517 --> 00:00:17.834
and it’s considered an adjustment
on a dish from the Indian subcontinent.

00:00:17.834 --> 00:00:20.138
which is called Kitchri, and is also made with rice and lentils.

00:00:20.138 --> 00:00:22.937
This was during British colonization in Egypt

00:00:22.937 --> 00:00:26.464
a part of whose forces came from British colonies in India

00:00:26.464 --> 00:00:32.291
 It is said to have been invented as a way to reduce food waste.

00:00:32.291 --> 00:00:39.627
Egyptians onions, which were a favorite in Egypt since the Pharaohs

00:00:39.627 --> 00:00:45.936
They also added pasta and tomato sauce which added contrast in texture and flavor

00:00:45.936 --> 00:00:51.961
Koshari has many variations, and is known in Cairo as a vegan dish.

00:00:51.961 --> 00:00:55.833
In Alexandria, they make it with Yellow lentils instead of brown

00:00:55.833 --> 00:00:59.521
and add liver or beef, and a different spice blend than the one used in Cairo.

00:00:59.521 --> 00:01:01.461
It is served with pickled tomatoes and French fries.

00:01:45.530 --> 00:01:49.037
Koshari’s popularity and cultural significance

00:01:49.037 --> 00:01:52.436
nspired internationally acclaimed Egyptian author Ahdaf Soueif

00:01:52.436 --> 00:01:56.753
to publish her recipe in The Guardian in 2009

00:01:56.753 --> 00:02:01.235
as an important document of culture sent to anyone who would like to make Koshari at home.

00:02:01.235 --> 00:02:06.565
Koshari remains a nutritious, affordable dish, beloved by all classes.

